{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651690"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:26:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:26:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18487"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18487","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18487"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11216"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77474"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11216"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18487"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62986"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6989"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26039"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26267"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26544"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77474"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe vagus nerve provides parasympathetic innervation to the gastrointestinal tract. It runs down through the oesophagus in close proximity to the oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical course of the vagal trunks in relation to the oesophagus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior trunk derived from right vagus nerve","Trunks form below the diaphragm","Both trunks contain fibres from left and right vagus nerves","Posterior trunk derived from left vagus nerve","Trunks pass through separate diaphragmatic openings"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoth trunks contain fibres from left and right vagus nerves\u003C/strong\u003E as they form anterior and posterior vagal trunks. This reorganisation occurs in the lower thorax, where fibres from both the left and right vagus nerves contribute to each trunk before passing through the oesophageal hiatus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior trunk derived from right vagus nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - The anterior trunk contains fibres from both vagal nerves, not just the right\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrunks form below the diaphragm\u003C/strong\u003E - The reorganisation occurs above the diaphragm in the lower thorax\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior trunk derived from left vagus nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - The posterior trunk contains fibres from both vagal nerves, not just the left\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrunks pass through separate diaphragmatic openings\u003C/strong\u003E - Both trunks pass through the oesophageal hiatus with the oesophagus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis arrangement ensures that if one vagus nerve is damaged in the neck or upper thorax, some innervation to the foregut will still be maintained through the contribution of the other nerve to both trunks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The vagus nerve provides parasympathetic innervation to the foregut from the oesophagus to the proximal two-thirds of the transverse colon.","The vagus nerve travels through the oesophageal hiatus of the diaphragm alongside the oesophagus.","The anterior and posterior vagal trunks form from the combination of left and right vagal fibres above the diaphragm."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18487"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62986"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T08:52:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T08:53:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11216"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77474"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca